==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Bleach
<hw>Bleach</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Bleached</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Bleaching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>blakien</ets>, <ets>blechen</ets>, v. t. & v. i., AS.
bl⟦amac⟧<ets>cian</ets>, <ets>bl⟦aemac⟧can</ets>, to grow pale; akin to
Icel. <ets>bleikja</ets>, Sw. <ets>bleka</ets>, Dan. <ets>blege</ets>,
D. <ets>bleeken</ets>, G. <ets>bleichen</ets>, AS. <ets>bl⟦amac⟧c</ets>
pale. See <er>Bleak</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>To make white, or
whiter; to remove the color, or stains, from; to blanch; to
whiten.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The destruction of the coloring matters attached to the bodies to
be <qex>bleached</qex> is effected either by the action of the air and
light, of chlorine, or of sulphurous acid.</q>
<rj><qau>Ure.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Immortal liberty, whose look sublime⟦br⟧
Hath <qex>bleached</qex> the tyrant's cheek in every varying clime.</q>
<rj><qau>Smollett.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Bleach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Bleach
<hw>Bleach</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow white or lose color; to
whiten.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

